01_hello.description:
Use `println!` to print a line.

```rust
println!("Hello, world!");
```

`println!` is a macro, so it ends with `!`.

```rust
let name = "Rust";
println!("Hello, {name}!");
```

Rust can insert variables directly into the format string.

03_ownership.description:
Moving transfers ownership.

```rust
let s = String::from("hi");
let t = s;
```

After that, `s` can no longer be used.

```rust
fn print_len(text: &String) {
    println!("{}", text.len());
}
```

`&String` borrows the value, so the original variable stays usable.

04_control_flow.description:
Use `if`, `while`, and `for` to control execution.

```rust
if x > 0 {
    println!("positive");
}
```

Ranges like `0..3` stop before the last number.

```rust
for n in 0..3 {
    println!("{n}");
}
```

This prints `0`, `1`, and `2`.

05_functions.description:
Functions declare parameter types and optional return types.

```rust
fn add(a: i32, b: i32) -> i32 {
    a + b
}
```

The last line has no semicolon, so it becomes the return value.

```rust
fn log_value(x: i32) {
    println!("{x}");
}
```

A trailing semicolon turns a line into a statement instead of a returned expression.

06_strings.description:
Use `&str` for borrowed text.

```rust
let name: &str = "Rust";
```

Use `String` for owned, growable text.

```rust
let mut name = String::from("Rust");
name.push('!');
```

`format!` builds and returns a new `String`.

07_tuples_arrays.description:
Tuples can mix types.

```rust
let pair = (1, "two");
let (a, b) = pair;
```

Arrays hold values of one type and a fixed length.

```rust
let nums = [10, 20, 30];
println!("{}", nums[0]);
```

The array length is part of its type.

09_structs.description:
A struct groups named fields.

```rust
struct User {
    name: String,
    age: u32,
}
```

An `impl` block adds methods.

```rust
impl User {
    fn is_adult(&self) -> bool {
        self.age >= 18
    }
}
```

10_closures_basic.description:
A closure is an anonymous function stored in a value.

```rust
let add = |a: i32, b: i32| a + b;
println!("{}", add(2, 3));
```

Rust often infers the types, so closures can stay compact.

11_closures_capture.description:
Closures can use values from the surrounding scope.

```rust
let mut count = 0;
let mut inc = || {
    count += 1;
};
```

Because the closure changes captured state, the closure binding itself must be `mut`.

12_iter_map.description:
`map` transforms each item in an iterator.

```rust
let nums = vec![1, 2, 3];
let doubled: Vec<i32> = nums.iter().map(|x| x * 2).collect();
```

`map` is lazy, so the work happens only when the iterator is consumed, such as by `collect()`.

13_iter_filter.description:
`filter` keeps only items that match a condition.

```rust
let nums = vec![1, 2, 3, 4];
let evens: Vec<i32> = nums.into_iter().filter(|n| n % 2 == 0).collect();
```

Like `map`, `filter` is lazy until the iterator is consumed.

14_iter_fold.description:
`fold` combines many items into one result.

```rust
let nums = [1, 2, 3];
let total = nums.iter().fold(0, |acc, n| acc + n);
```

The first argument is the starting accumulator.

15_iter_sum.description:
Methods like `sum()` and `max()` consume an iterator and return a final result.

```rust
let nums = vec![1, 2, 3];
let total: i32 = nums.iter().sum();
```

`sum()` often needs a type annotation so Rust knows the output type.

16_traits_basic.description:
A trait describes shared behavior.

```rust
trait Greet {
    fn greet(&self);
}
```

A type implements the trait like this.

```rust
impl Greet for Person {
    fn greet(&self) {
        println!("hi");
    }
}
```

17_traits_default.description:
Trait methods can have default behavior.

```rust
trait Speak {
    fn sound(&self) -> &'static str {
        "..."
    }
}
```

A type may override that method, but it does not have to.

19_generics_basic.description:
Generics let one function work with many types.

```rust
fn largest<T: PartialOrd + Copy>(a: T, b: T) -> T {
    if a > b { a } else { b }
}
```

`T: PartialOrd + Copy` means `T` must support comparison and cheap copying.

20_lifetimes_basic.description:
Lifetimes describe how long references stay valid.

```rust
fn longest<'a>(x: &'a str, y: &'a str) -> &'a str {
    if x.len() > y.len() { x } else { y }
}
```

`'a` tells Rust the returned reference cannot outlive the input references.

23_option_basic.description:
`Option<T>` means a value may or may not exist.

```rust
let name = Some("Rust");
let empty: Option<&str> = None;
```

`unwrap_or` gives the value or a fallback.

```rust
println!("{}", empty.unwrap_or("none"));
```

24_error_propagation.description:
The `?` operator unwraps success and returns early on failure.

```rust
fn read_num(text: &str) -> Result<i32, std::num::ParseIntError> {
    let n = text.parse()?;
    Ok(n)
}
```

This works only inside functions that return `Result` or `Option`.

25_panic_unwrap.description:
`unwrap()` and `expect()` extract the inner value.

```rust
let value = Some(10);
println!("{}", value.unwrap());
```

If the value is missing, the program panics.

```rust
let missing: Option<i32> = None;
missing.expect("value should exist");
```

26_async_basic.description:
`async fn` returns a future.

```rust
async fn fetch() -> i32 {
    42
}
```

The function body does not finish immediately. Something must await or poll the future.

```rust
let value = pollster::block_on(fetch());
```

27_box_basic.description:
`Box<T>` stores a value on the heap.

```rust
let n = Box::new(5);
println!("{}", n);
```

It is useful for heap allocation and recursive data structures.

28_rc_basic.description:
`Rc<T>` lets multiple variables share ownership.

```rust
use std::rc::Rc;
let a = Rc::new(String::from("hi"));
let b = Rc::clone(&a);
```

The value is dropped only when the last `Rc` is gone. `Rc` is for single-threaded code.

29_refcell_basic.description:
`RefCell<T>` allows interior mutability.

```rust
use std::cell::RefCell;
let cell = RefCell::new(5);
*cell.borrow_mut() += 1;
```

The borrow rules are checked at runtime instead of compile time.

30_macros_basic.description:
Built-in macros end with `!`.

```rust
let v = vec![1, 2, 3];
println!("{:?}", v);
let text = format!("{}+{}={}", 2, 3, 5);
```

Macros expand into code at compile time.

31_macros_custom.description:
`macro_rules!` defines a declarative macro.

```rust
macro_rules! say_hi {
    () => {
        println!("hi");
    };
}
```

The macro matches a pattern and expands into regular Rust code.

32_unsafe_basic.description:
`unsafe` allows operations Rust cannot verify automatically.

```rust
let mut x = 10;
let p: *mut i32 = &mut x;
unsafe {
    *p += 1;
}
```

This does not disable the whole language. It only allows specific unsafe actions inside the block.

33_vec_push.description:
`Vec<T>` is Rust's growable array type.

```rust
let mut nums = vec![1, 2];
nums.push(3);
```

`push()` appends a value to the end of the vector.

35_arc_mutex.description:
`Arc<T>` shares ownership across threads.

```rust
use std::sync::{Arc, Mutex};
let count = Arc::new(Mutex::new(0));
```

`Mutex<T>` protects mutable shared data.

```rust
let mut value = count.lock().unwrap();
*value += 1;
```

36_iter_enumerate.description:
`enumerate()` adds an index to each item.

```rust
for (index, name) in names.iter().enumerate() {
    println!("{index}: {name}");
}
```

Because each item is a tuple, the loop pattern must use parentheses.
